Air Quality Index in Mainland China

Andi Liao

Introduction to AQI

Overall Distrbution of Air Pollution across Maindland China

Overall, the air pollution is a national wide issue, and it is getting worse with the development of time. The spatial distribution of air pollution are heterogeneous. The air quality in the northern part is less satisfying because of colder climate, less forest coverage and more focus on heavy industry.

ann_text <- data.frame(
                       x = 90, 
                       y = 60,
                       lab = "Text",
                       year = factor(2014, levels = c("2008", "2011", "2014")))

g0 <-
      merged_data %>%
      ggplot() + 
      geom_sf(
              aes(fill = value), 
              color = "#696969") +

                    y = 57,

g0

Factors Contributing to Nationalwide Air Pollution

Sulfur Dioxide and Smoke

The major source of air pollutants in China is sulfur dioxide emitted from factories, because the energy structure is currently dominated by coal. The central government has released a series of policies to control the concentration and emissions of sulfur dioxide. Although AQI is not the best indicator of sulfur dioxide pollution, areas highly polluted by sulfur dioxide usually suffer from other air pollutants as well. Smoke is served as a reference here.

g11 <-
      data_long %>%
      select(-("metrics")) %>%
      filter(measurement == "aqi" | measurement == "sulfur") %>%
      spread(measurement, value) %>%
      mutate(category = cut(sulfur, breaks = c(0, 70, Inf),
                            labels = c("low", "high"))) %>%
      group_by(category) %>%
    
      ggplot(
             aes(x = year, 
                 y = aqi, 
                 fill = category)) + 
      scale_fill_manual(values =  c("#486824", "#F2C057")) +
      geom_violin(
                  position = position_dodge(width = 0.6),
                  width = 0.8, 
                  alpha = 0.4) +
      geom_boxplot(
                   position = position_dodge(width = 0.6), 
                   width = 0.1, 
                   alpha = 0.7) +
      ylim(30, 150) +
      theme_new() +
      theme(
            plot.margin = unit(c(0.2, 0.2, 0.2, 0.2), "cm")) +
      labs(
            x = "Year",
            y = "AQI",
            fill = "Sulfur Dioxide")

p <-
  data_long %>%
  select(-("metrics")) %>%
  filter(measurement == "aqi") %>%
  spread(measurement, value) %>%
  group_by(region) %>%
  summarise(aqi = mean(aqi)) %>% 
  rownames_to_column("province") %>%
  arrange(aqi) %>%
  mutate(region = factor(region, levels = .$region)) %>%
  mutate(is_south = south_prov)

g2 <-
  p %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = aqi, y = region)) +
  geom_segment(aes(x = 0, xend = aqi, y = region, yend = region, color = factor(is_south)), alpha = 0.9) +
  geom_point(aes(color = factor(is_south)), size = 1, alpha = 0.9) +
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0), limits = c(0, 120)) +
  scale_y_discrete(limits = rev(levels(p$region))) +
  scale_color_manual(labels = c("No","Yes"), values = c("#92AAC7", "#EC96A4")) +
  theme_new() + 
  theme(panel.grid.major.y = element_blank()) +
  labs(
      title = wrapper("Provinces in the southern part of China have better air quality.", width = 70),
      subtitle = wrapper("Calculate the average AQI grouped by province of year 2008, 2011 and 2014, and the ordered result shows that most southern provinces have lower average AQI. The only exception is Tibet, the plateau area in the western part.", width = 90),
      caption = "Peking University Open Research Data Platform",
      x = "Air Quality Index", 
      y = "Province",
      color = "Southern Part") 

g2

Forest Coverage and Population

Population doesnt affect air quality much, but the forest coverage rate does. Interestingly, provinces with worse air quality all have relatively less forest coverage, but their population vary from low to high. The natural environment factor plays a key role in air quality here.

p <-
    data_long %>%
    select(-("metrics")) %>%
    filter(measurement == "aqi" | measurement == "forest" | measurement == "population") %>%
    spread(measurement, value) %>%
    group_by(region) %>%
    summarise(
              aqi = mean(aqi), 
              forest = mean(forest), 
              population = mean(population)) 

g3 <-  
      p %>%
      ggplot(
             aes(x = forest, 
                 y = aqi, 
                 color = population, 
                 fill = population, 
                 size = population)) + 
      geom_point(shape = 23) +
      scale_color_continuous(
                             low = "#FEF3E2",
                             high = "#85A65E", 
                             guide = FALSE) +
      scale_fill_continuous(
                            low = "#FEF3E2",
                            high = "#85A65E", 
                            label = scales::comma) +
      scale_size_continuous(
                            range = c(6, 18),
                            guide = FALSE) +
      xlim(3, 65) +
      ylim(35, 120) +
      geom_text_repel(
                      aes(forest, aqi, label = region), 
                      size = 3, 
                      family = "Georgia",
                      color = "#525252") +
      theme_new() + 
      theme(
           legend.key.width = unit(1 ,"cm")) +
      labs(
          title = wrapper("Provinces with higher forest coverage have better air quality.", width = 120),
          subtitle = wrapper("With the increase of forest coverage rate, the air quality becomes better despite the changes of population.", width = 140),
          caption = "Peking University Open Research Data Platform",
          x = "Forest Coverage",
          y = "AQI",
          fill = "Population")

Temporal Changes of Air Quality in Beijing

Policy Changes and Political Events

Beijing government started a series of campaign to control the air pollution. For example, the one of the largest scale is called changing from coal to gas in the winter of 2017. The air quality was largely improved after the campaign, compared to previous years. However, Beijing still has a long way to go to reduce the days with heavy pollution.

g5

Year-to-Year Comparasion

Beijing lies in the northern part of China, and it is the most populated city in the country. It is also well-known for sandstorm and haze, but the local government has made efforts to mitigate the air pollution. The weekly average air quality of Beijing is improving. However, there always some terrible days within in the winter, as there are high demands of heating and large number of factories working towards the deadline before Lunar New Year. Plantations have been planted in the north border, which prevents wind coming from the North and take the air pollutants away sometimes during the winter.

g4

Month-to-Hour Comparasion

Breaking down by month and hour, the winter has serious air pollution problem. During the winter, the air quality in the mornings and evenings are worse than afternoons, partially because people need more heat before the sun comes out and after the sun comes down. Actually, it is the horrible pollution in the winter of 2016 that pushes Beijing government to launch the biggest ever changing from coal to gas project in the winter of 2017.

a = rbind(AQI_2018, AQI_2017, AQI_2016, AQI_2015)
a$date = ymd(a$date)

g6 <-
      a %>%
      filter(metrics == "PM2.5") %>%
      group_by(bigmonth = month(date), hour) %>%
      summarise(PM2.5 = mean(value, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
      ggplot(
            aes(x = as.factor(hour), 
                y = reorder(as.factor(bigmonth), desc(as.factor(bigmonth))), 
                fill = PM2.5)) + 
      geom_tile() + 
      scale_fill_gradient(
                          low = "#FEF3E2", 
                          high = "#D13525",
                          limits = c(30, 120),
                          breaks = c(30, 60, 90, 120),
                          labels = c("30", "60", "90", "120")) +
      scale_y_discrete(labels = c("Dec", "Nov", "Oct", "Sep", "Aug", "Jul", "Jun", "May", "Apr", "Mar", "Feb", "Jan")) +
      theme_new() +
      theme(
            legend.key.width = unit(1, "cm")) +
      labs(
            title = wrapper(" PM 2.5 is higher during winter nights in Beijing.", width = 120),
            subtitle = wrapper("The air quality is better in summer, worse in winter based on monthly average from 2015 to 2018. Winter nights are extremely bad because of heating. The exception is March, where Beijing suffers from sandstroms typically.", width = 125),
            caption = "National Urban Air Quality in Real-Time Publishing Platform",
            x = "Hour", 
            y = "Month")

Spatial Distribution of Air Quality in Beijing

Uneven Distribution Across Years

The distribution of air population is highly uneven in terms of districts, but things are getting better. The southern part of Beijing experienced more serious air pollution than the other parts, but the overall trend is that the air pollution is being mitigated after 2017. This observation is in consistent with the policy changes displayed above.

g8

Uneven Distribution of Domainant Polluants

The dominant pollutant in each district of Beijing is different. The southern part of Beijing have higher PM2.5 and PM10. The middle part have higher NO2 and S02. The northern part have higher O3. This distribution is the result of climate conditions and industry adjustment over the years. In order to reach the emission standards designed by the central government, Beijing is gradually transferring some of its responsibilities to nearby cities, including moving factories away.
